{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"6e8c176f-a9db-4d83-8a01-a9f9e86b3b25","content":"Here's my analysis:\n\n## Root Cause\n\nThe developer report confirms the overhead is from **MSBuild process startup and project re-evaluation** on every `dotnet build` invocation — not from actual compilation. Visual Studio avoids this by keeping MSBuild nodes resident in memory.\n\n## Recommendations (in order of impact)\n\n### 1. Use `--no-restore` for repeat builds\nBy default, `dotnet build` runs a NuGet restore every time. Skip it when packages haven't changed:\n```bash\ndotnet build --no-restore\n```\n\n### 2. Use `dotnet watch` for the inner loop\nThis keeps the process resident and rebuilds on file changes — eliminating startup cost entirely:\n```bash\ndotnet watch build\n```\n\n### 3. Ensure MSBuild node reuse is enabled\nMSBuild can keep worker nodes alive between invocations. Verify the environment variable `MSBUILDDISABLENODEREUSE` is **not** set to `1`:\n```bash\n# Check current setting\necho $MSBUILDDISABLENODEREUSE\n\n# If set to 1, unset it to allow reuse\nunset MSBUILDDISABLENODEREUSE\n```\n\n### 4. Use terminal logger to reduce output overhead (.NET 8+)\n```bash\ndotnet build --tl:quiet --no-restore\n```\n\n### Summary\n\n| Approach | Saves | Best For |\n|---|---|---|\n| `--no-restore` | ~0.5-1s per build | Every CLI build |\n| `dotnet watch build` | All startup overhead | Active edit-build cycles |\n| Node reuse | ~0.5-1s per build | Frequent CLI builds |\n| `--tl:quiet` | Minor I/O overhead | Large output projects |\n\nThe single biggest win for the \"edit → build → test\" inner loop is **`dotnet watch`**, since it mirrors what VS does by keeping the build host warm. For ad-hoc CLI builds, **`--no-restore`** is the easiest quick win.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"fd882bec-632a-4a62-a735-fb94da07c471","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The developer reports that `dotnet build` from CLI is slow for incremental builds (2-4 seconds even when nothing changed), while Visual Studio rebuilds nearly instantly. They've ruled out analyzers and confirmed incremental build targets work correctly. The overhead is from MSBuild process startup and project graph re-evaluation.\n\nThe key insight here is that Visual Studio uses an MSBuild server process that stays resident in memory, avoiding the cold-start overhead on each build. The CLI equivalent is the **MSBuild Server** (also known as the build server or `dotnet build-server`).\n\nHere are the main recommendations:\n\n1. **Use `dotnet build-server`** - .NET 8+ supports an MSBuild server that keeps the build process warm between invocations, similar to VS. \n\nYou can enable this via the `DOTNET_CLI_USE_MSBUILD_SERVER=1` environment variable or the `-server` flag.\n\n2. **Use `dotnet watch build`** - This keeps the process running and watches for file changes, eliminating the startup cost entirely.\n\n3. **Enable the MSBuild graph build** - The `-graph` flag can optimize multi-project solutions.\n\n4. **Use `dotnet build --no-restore`** - Skip the NuGet restore step if packages haven't changed.\n\nThe real bottleneck is the MSBuild process startup time and project graph re-evaluation on each invocation, so the server approach directly addresses this by keeping the process warm between builds. I need to clarify the exact mechanisms for speeding up .NET CLI builds—the MSBuild server feature and node reuse settings are the key levers, along with skipping restore when dependencies haven't changed and leveraging graph-based builds for parallel compilation. The biggest performance gains come from avoiding redundant restore operations and keeping MSBuild worker processes alive between invocations. actionable answer about CLI build performance.","outputTokens":1459},"id":"22d89075-8c38-43ef-ad31-04078890ec0b","timestamp":"2026-04-05T00:53:58.906Z","parentId":"0c5c2877-cfd3-4cd8-88bd-fbe90450a261"}
